{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502862","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502862"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:51:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1906"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1906"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.22,0.23,0.07,0.02,0.45]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103644"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1906","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1906"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1906"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86061"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"2115"},{"type":"tags","id":"6373"},{"type":"tags","id":"8116"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1780"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11759"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103644","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103644"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her local Emergency Department (ED) with a history of sudden onset left flank pain, nausea and vomiting. A CT KUB (non-contrast) is performed which demonstrates a 2mm distal left ureteric stone. There is also an incidental finding of a 2.4cm non-cystic mass arising from the upper pole of the right kidney. She is planned for discharge home with analgesia to pass the stone spontaneously. She requires follow-up regarding this renal mass.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in the investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT-guided renal biopsy of lesion","CT abdomen/pelvis with contrast","Renal tract ultrasound","Right laparoscopic renal biopsy","Surveillance CT KUB in six months"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has an incidental finding of a small renal mass (\u0026lt;3cm). The next step in management is to get further information to ascertain whether the mass is malignant or not. Since the initial imaging suggests this is a non-cystic mass, further detailed information is required and this is best accomplished by further characterising the lesion with a \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrast-enhanced CT abdomen/pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E. Renal malignancies are vascular and thus the mass will enhance (defined as an increase in Hounsfield of \u0026gt;20 units). If the mass enhances and it is likely to be a small renal tumour, it could still be observed with serial imaging to establish its growth rate. With renal tumours of this size the risk of developing metastases within three years of diagnosis is very small and about 1%. If there was still diagnostic doubt after the contrast-enhanced CT scan, a biopsy to confirm diagnosis could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf it is determined that that this lesion is a small renal neoplasm, a decision can then be made for intervention or active surveillance. In older patients (age \u0026gt;70) and those with co-mobidities, follow-up with active surveillance would be quite appropriate. In those cases the options of further radiological assessment will include CT and ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this mass was cystic, the Bosniak classification could be used to determine the risk of malignancy and decide whether such a patient would require some form of active intervention or surveillance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Small renal tumours (\u003C3 cm) have a slow rate of growth and in older, unfit patients can be managed with active surveillance."],"references":["Campell SC, Clark PE, Chang SS et al: Renal Mass and Localized Renal Cancer: Evaluation, Management, and Follow-Up: AUA Guideline Part I. J Urol 2021; 206: 199.","Schieda N, Krishna S, Pedrosa I, et al. Active Surveillance of Renal Masses: The Role of Radiology. Radiology 2022; 302:11\u201324"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86061"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1906"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86061","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86061"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-25T09:55:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-25T09:55:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1906"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103644"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":nul